### Control-Constructs:- 
   --> Control constructs determine the order in which statements in a Java program are executed.
             ↓
             ↓
   1. Conditional
             ↓
   => Conditional control constructs allow a program to make decisions based on conditions.
              ↓
       if Statement
              ↓ 
 =>Executes a block only if condition is true.
 E.g:-       if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible to vote");
}
  2. if–else Statement
            ↓
 Chooses between two blocks
             ↓
condition → true  → block A
          → false → block B
              ↓
E.g :- if (marks >= 40) {
    System.out.println("Pass");
} else {
    System.out.println("Fail");
}
 3. Else-if
       ↓
-> Used when multiple conditions are checked
        ↓
 cond1 → true → block1
     → false → cond2 → block2
     → false → cond3 → block3
     → false → else block
         ↓
     if (marks >= 90) {
         grade = 'A';
    } else if (marks >= 75) {
        grade = 'B';
     } else if (marks >= 60) {
           grade = 'C';
     } else {
    grade = 'D';
}

4.    switch Statement
        ↓
       Selects execution based on expression value
=> expression → case → execute → break
            ↓
E.g:- switch (day) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid day");
}
         ↓
5. Ternary Operator (?:)
         ↓
 Short form of if–else
          ↓
condition ? value_if_true : value_if_false
 ###    2. Looping 
      -> Repeat execution
      i.  for Loop
       for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}
      ii. while Loop
       while (i <= 5) {
    i++;
} 
    iii. do-while loop
          ↓
         do {
    i++;
} while (i <= 5);
    
3. Jumping
   --> Jumping constructs are used to transfer control immediately from one part of a program to another.
                            ↓
                            ↓
    i. break
         ↓
-> Terminates the loop or switch statement.
-->     loop / switch → break → exit
             ↓
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i == 3) break;
    System.out.println(i);
}

ii. continue
        ↓
-> Skips the current iteration and moves to the next one.
        ↓
--> loop → continue → next iteration
        ↓
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i == 3) continue;
    System.out.println(i);
}
iii. return
       ↓
 -->  Exits from a method and sends control back to the calling method.
       ↓
method → return → caller
       ↓
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

